description.narrative: (Kenya): .The Health Communications and Marketing (HCM) activity.supports social behaviour change (SBC) interventions to increase demand and.uptake of health services. To shift from a dependance mindset to a.self-reliance mindset, behavior change is required to increase Kenyan.commitment. Additionally, local ownership and sustainability beyond donor.funding is a key focus of Kenya's journey to self-reliance. The community.to county level approach to designing and implementing SBC interventions.ensures local ownership and leadership, requiring intentional selection of.stakeholders who will be accountable for carrying activities forward. This.approach links health facilities and utilizes the existing cadre of community.health volunteers, which the Government of Kenya supports. HCM will support SBC.activities focused on increasing utilization of health services for HIV, family.planning, maternal, newborn and child health, and malaria through targeted.multi-channelled SBC strategies. In priority counties targeting the most.vulnerable and high priority populations, the focus of SBC activities will be.on increasing the uptake of postnatal care services, routine immunization,.prevention and treatment of diarrheal diseases through the community health.platform, increasing net utilization, early and appropriate health-seeking.behaviour, and prompt diagnosis and treatment for all people with fever. HCM.will provide technical assistance to the National Malaria Control Program and.the lake endemic counties to fulfill their advocacy, communication, and social.behavior change roles as defined in the Kenya Malaria Strategy. This activity.supports the promotion of a more healthy Kenya, which is a key American.economic, trading, and security partner in an often volatile East African region..By strengthening Kenya's health care system, USAID is helping to strengthen an.important regional ally..... .
